Yes. Since AS400’s contract may use either camelCase or snake_case, you can support both without changing the global Jackson configuration.

For each field where the incoming name may differ, use `@JsonProperty` for the preferred API name and `@JsonAlias` for the alternative.

Example for the root request:

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonAlias;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonProperty;
import jakarta.validation.Valid;
import jakarta.validation.constraints.NotNull;
import lombok.Getter;
import lombok.Setter;

@Getter
@Setter
public class As400UserSnapshotRequest {

    @Valid
    @NotNull
    @JsonProperty("metadata")
    private As400MetadataRequest metadata;

    @Valid
    @NotNull
    @JsonProperty("source")
    private As400SourceRequest source;

    @Valid
    @NotNull
    @JsonProperty("person")
    private As400PersonRequest person;

    @Valid
    @NotNull
    @JsonProperty("point_of_sales")
    @JsonAlias("pointOfSales")
    private As400PointOfSalesRequest pointOfSales;

    @Valid
    @NotNull
    @JsonProperty("working_relationship")
    @JsonAlias("workingRelationship")
    private As400WorkingRelationshipRequest workingRelationship;
}
```

For nested DTOs, do the same.

```java
@Getter
@Setter
public class As400MetadataRequest {

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("source_system")
    @JsonAlias("sourceSystem")
    private String sourceSystem;

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("correlation_id")
    @JsonAlias("correlationId")
    private String correlationId;

    @NotNull
    @JsonProperty("snapshot_timestamp")
    @JsonAlias("snapshotTimestamp")
    private Instant snapshotTimestamp;

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("payload_version")
    @JsonAlias("payloadVersion")
    private String payloadVersion;
}
```

```java
@Getter
@Setter
public class As400SourceRequest {

    @NotBlank
    private String entity;

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("source_record_type")
    @JsonAlias("sourceRecordType")
    private String sourceRecordType;

    @JsonProperty("source_personal_id")
    @JsonAlias("sourcePersonalId")
    private String sourcePersonalId;

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("gps_group_number")
    @JsonAlias("gpsGroupNumber")
    private String gpsGroupNumber;

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("source_point_of_sales_id")
    @JsonAlias("sourcePointOfSalesId")
    private String sourcePointOfSalesId;
}
```

```java
@Getter
@Setter
public class As400PersonRequest {

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("first_name")
    @JsonAlias("firstName")
    private String firstName;

    @NotBlank
    private String surname;

    @Email
    @NotBlank
    private String email;

    @JsonProperty("phone_number")
    @JsonAlias("phoneNumber")
    private String phoneNumber;

    @NotBlank
    private String language;

    @NotBlank
    private String status;
}
```

```java
@Getter
@Setter
public class As400WorkingRelationshipRequest {

    @NotBlank
    @JsonProperty("relationship_type")
    @JsonAlias("relationshipType")
    private String relationshipType;

    @JsonProperty("parent_dealer_id")
    @JsonAlias("parentDealerId")
    private String parentDealerId;

    @NotBlank
    private String status;
}
```

For `As400PointOfSalesRequest`, `id` and `name` do not need aliases because both styles are the same.

Use **snake_case as the official AS400 contract** in Swagger/OpenAPI, because it matches the rest of your Partner Repository API. `@JsonAlias` simply makes local testing and future integrations more forgiving.

Then both payload styles will work:

```json
{ "point_of_sales": { "id": "POS001", "name": "Orange Shop Brussels" } }
```

and:

```json
{ "pointOfSales": { "id": "POS001", "name": "Orange Shop Brussels" } }
```
